<paragraph blockId="73.[264,1324,1769,1875]" lastBlockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" lastPageId="74" lastPageNumber="75" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
Pronotum slightly transverse, width 
<quantity box="[753,864,1769,1795]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" unit="mm" value="0.41">0.41 mm</quantity>
, width to length ratio 1.0, wider than head (pronotal width to head width ratio 
<number box="[742,781,1809,1835]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" value="1.1">1.1</number>
); microsculpture and puncturation as on head. Pronotal pubescence of 
<typeStatus box="[551,602,1849,1875]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">type</typeStatus>
V. Elytra measured from humeral angle longer than pronotum (pronotal length to elytral length ratio 1.0), wider than long (
<number box="[1035,1075,284,310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="1.3">1.3</number>
), with weak and fine isodiametric microsculpture and fine, somewhat asperate puncturation, distance between punctures equals 
<number box="[469,508,364,390]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2­3</number>
times their diameter. Elytral suture behind scutellum raised. Wings fully developed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Abdominal terga with fine microsculpture of transverse meshes, with fine and sparse puncturation, puncturation becoming finer towards abdomen apex, on terga 
<number box="[1178,1217,484,510]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3­5</number>
distance between punctures equals 
<number box="[572,611,524,550]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="4.0" valueMax="5.0" valueMin="3.0">3­5</number>
times their diameter. Tergum 
<number box="[972,987,524,550]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="7.0">7</number>
with white edge.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Male tergum 
<number box="[473,488,564,590]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="7.0">7</number>
with two medial carinae in front of posterior margin. Male tergum 
<number box="[1309,1324,564,590]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="8.0">8</number>
with four small carinae in front of posterior margin, posterior margin slightly convex (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 321 ­ 326" captionStartId="72.[264,383,1696,1720]" captionTargetBox="[286,1297,660,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1311,649,1670]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 321 ­ 326. Abdominal segment 8 and aedeagus of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 321 – male tergum 8; 322 – male sternum 8; 323 – median lobe, ventral view; 324 – apex of median lobe, ventral view; 325 – median lobe, lateral view; 326 – apex of median lobe, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (321 ­ 323, 325), 0.2 mm (324, 326)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155746/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<number box="[264,312,644,670]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="321.0">321</number>
</figureCitation>
). Male sternum 
<number box="[509,524,644,670]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="8.0">8</number>
with convex posterior margin (
<figureCitation box="[893,997,644,670]" captionStart="FIGURES 321 ­ 326" captionStartId="72.[264,383,1696,1720]" captionTargetBox="[286,1297,660,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1311,649,1670]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 321 ­ 326. Abdominal segment 8 and aedeagus of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 321 – male tergum 8; 322 – male sternum 8; 323 – median lobe, ventral view; 324 – apex of median lobe, ventral view; 325 – median lobe, lateral view; 326 – apex of median lobe, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (321 ­ 323, 325), 0.2 mm (324, 326)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155746/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<number box="[948,997,644,670]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="322.0">322</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Aedeagus as in 
<figureCitation box="[507,678,684,710]" captionStart-0="FIGURES 321 ­ 326" captionStart-1="FIGURES 327 ­ 335" captionStartId-0="72.[264,383,1696,1720]" captionStartId-1="73.[264,383,1480,1504]" captionTargetBox-0="[286,1297,660,1656]" captionTargetBox-1="[307,1280,824,1441]" captionTargetId-0="figure@72.[275,1311,649,1670]" captionTargetId-1="figure@73.[296,1290,809,1454]" captionTargetPageId-0="72" captionTargetPageId-1="73" captionText-0="FIGURES 321 ­ 326. Abdominal segment 8 and aedeagus of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 321 – male tergum 8; 322 – male sternum 8; 323 – median lobe, ventral view; 324 – apex of median lobe, ventral view; 325 – median lobe, lateral view; 326 – apex of median lobe, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (321 ­ 323, 325), 0.2 mm (324, 326)." captionText-1="FIGURES 327 ­ 335. Genitalia of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 327 – details of internal sac retracted into median lobe, ventral view; 328 – copulatory piece of internal sac, dorsal view; 329 – distal diverticula of everted internal sac, ventral view; 330 – everted internal sac, ventral view; 331 – everted internal sac, lateral view; 332 ­ 333 – details of internal sac retracted into median lobe, lateral view; 334 – apex of left paramere, side facing median lobe; 335 – copulatory piece of internal sac, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (327, 330 ­ 333), 0.2 mm (328 ­ 329, 334 ­ 335)." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/155746/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/155747/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number box="[576,678,684,710]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="329.0" valueMax="335.0" valueMin="323.0">323­335</number>
</figureCitation>
. Apex of median lobe in lateral view bent ventrally (
<figureCitation box="[273,441,724,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 321 ­ 326" captionStartId="72.[264,383,1696,1720]" captionTargetBox="[286,1297,660,1656]" captionTargetId="figure@72.[275,1311,649,1670]" captionTargetPageId="72" captionText="FIGURES 321 ­ 326. Abdominal segment 8 and aedeagus of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 321 – male tergum 8; 322 – male sternum 8; 323 – median lobe, ventral view; 324 – apex of median lobe, ventral view; 325 – median lobe, lateral view; 326 – apex of median lobe, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (321 ­ 323, 325), 0.2 mm (324, 326)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155746/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number box="[339,441,724,750]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="325.5" valueMax="326.0" valueMin="325.0">325­326</number>
</figureCitation>
), distal diverticula of internal sac in ventral view wide (
<figureCitation box="[1094,1263,724,750]" captionStart="FIGURES 327 ­ 335" captionStartId="73.[264,383,1480,1504]" captionTargetBox="[307,1280,824,1441]" captionTargetId="figure@73.[296,1290,809,1454]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="FIGURES 327 ­ 335. Genitalia of Geostiba silvigena Gusarov, sp. n. (holotype). 327 – details of internal sac retracted into median lobe, ventral view; 328 – copulatory piece of internal sac, dorsal view; 329 – distal diverticula of everted internal sac, ventral view; 330 – everted internal sac, ventral view; 331 – everted internal sac, lateral view; 332 ­ 333 – details of internal sac retracted into median lobe, lateral view; 334 – apex of left paramere, side facing median lobe; 335 – copulatory piece of internal sac, lateral view. Scale bar 0.4 mm (327, 330 ­ 333), 0.2 mm (328 ­ 329, 334 ­ 335)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155747/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number box="[1160,1263,724,750]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="329.5" valueMax="330.0" valueMin="329.0">329­330</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" box="[312,523,764,790]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Female unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,451,803,829]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[472,694,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvigena">
<emphasis box="[472,694,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Geostiba silvigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has fully developed wings and it is probably widespread along the Pacific coast of North 
<collectingCountry box="[722,827,844,870]" name="United States of America" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">America</collectingCountry>
. The species may not be active in summer when most collections in the area have been made (see the above discussion of natural history of 
<taxonomicName box="[351,515,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="impressula">
<emphasis box="[351,515,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">G. impressula</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). Although 
<taxonomicName box="[666,809,924,949]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvigena">
<emphasis box="[666,809,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">G. silvigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is closely related to the eastern Nearctic 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appalachigena">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">G. appalachigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the westernmost locality of 
<taxonomicName box="[784,995,964,989]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="appalachigena">
<emphasis box="[784,995,964,989]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">G. appalachigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is in Wisconsin (
<figureCitation captionStart-0="FIGURE 336" captionStart-1="FIGURE 337" captionStartId-0="76.[264,368,1562,1586]" captionStartId-1="77.[264,367,1248,1272]" captionTargetBox-0="[315,1271,753,1543]" captionTargetBox-1="[328,1262,539,1226]" captionTargetId-0="figure@76.[311,1275,751,1546]" captionTargetId-1="figure@77.[321,1266,529,1233]" captionTargetPageId-0="76" captionTargetPageId-1="77" captionText-0="FIGURE 336. Geographical distribution of Nearctic species of Geostiba. The ellipse indicates the area where eleven Southern Appalachian species are distributed." captionText-1="FIGURE 337. Geographical distribution of Geostiba appalachigena Gusarov, sp. n. The ellipse indicates the area where eleven Southern Appalachian species are distributed." httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/155748/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/155749/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Figs. 
<number pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="336.5" valueMax="337.0" valueMin="336.0">336­ 337</number>
</figureCitation>
). Considering the gap between the ranges of the two species and the minor difference in male genitalia the separate status of the two seems justified.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" box="[312,1295,1083,1110]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,663,1083,1109]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Distribution and variability.</emphasis>
Known only from Mendocino, California (
<figureCitation box="[1179,1282,1084,1110]" captionStart="FIGURE 336" captionStartId="76.[264,368,1562,1586]" captionTargetBox="[315,1271,753,1543]" captionTargetId="figure@76.[311,1275,751,1546]" captionTargetPageId="76" captionText="FIGURE 336. Geographical distribution of Nearctic species of Geostiba. The ellipse indicates the area where eleven Southern Appalachian species are distributed." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155748/files/figure.png" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
Fig. 
<number box="[1233,1282,1084,1110]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" value="336.0">336</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,517,1123,1149]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Natural History.</emphasis>
The only known specimen of 
<taxonomicName box="[884,1026,1124,1149]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Geostiba" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="74" pageNumber="75" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="silvigena">
<emphasis box="[884,1026,1124,1149]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">G. silvigena</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
was collected in moss in the bed of a dried up woodland pool.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="74" pageNumber="75" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="74.[264,1324,284,1310]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,453,1203,1229]" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific name is derived from the Latin noun 
<emphasis box="[1088,1143,1204,1229]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">silva</emphasis>
(forest, woodland) and the verb 
<emphasis box="[492,559,1244,1269]" italics="true" pageId="74" pageNumber="75">gigno</emphasis>
(to be born, to arise). It refers to the habitat where the species presumably occurs.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
